		<Placemark id="5984C714B800002E">
			<name>Ayyy Flooded</name>
			<snippet></snippet>
			<description><![CDATA[<div>Ayyy Flooded<br></div><div>GPS -37.716057, 144.952149<br></div><div>MELWAYS REF. 17 E-5<br></div><div>LOCATION: East side of Sussex St between Caringa &amp; South Sts in cemetery grounds. Hop over 1.8m high fence.<br></div><div>ENTRANCE: 1.4 ⭕<br></div><div>OTHER SHAPES: ⛰<br></div><div>CLAN ZONE: North<br></div><div>⛔ Shin deep outlet<br></div><div>VALUE: 🙂🙂<br></div><div>CLEANLINESS: Okay unless you slip<br></div><div>TRANSPORT: Upfield train to Merlynston or tram 19 to end of line for outlet<br></div><div>HIGHLIGHT: Boat trip pre-97, now shapes<br></div><div>PROBLEMS: Low sections. Ghosts!<br></div><div>NEARBY: Dead, DIPS, Bell Stairway, The Falls, Fox Hole &amp; Pentridge<br></div><div>NOTES: Go with the flow. In the past, the last 150m was flooded &amp; a boat was required. In 1996, the creek was dug out to lower the water-level finishing the pleasant boat trip expeditions ☹<br></div><div>The first time we explored this drain we tied a rope to a rubber boat &amp; sent Cobra in. “Don’t let the rope go” he pleaded. He struggled up against the flow around the bend into the darkness not knowing what lay ahead. He’d call out every now and then “Ayyy, are you still there”, and we’d give a tug on the rope to let him know we were. After about five minutes the rope got down to its last meters. Doug rigged the rope for as long as possible. Cobra was up a drain without a paddle or a lifeline. In the distance, if we listened carefully, we could hear… “Ayyy, ayyy… you there?”<br></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_0920FA33F53E916505AE</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>144.952149,-37.716057,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="5984C714B800002F">
			<name>Bad</name>
			<snippet></snippet>
			<description><![CDATA[<div>Bad<br></div><div>🚲 🍸<br></div><div>GPS -37.865142, 145.100553<br></div><div>MELWAYS REF. 60 J-10<br></div><div>LOCATION: Follow Gardiners Creek against the flow for five minutes from High Street Rd<br></div><div>ENTRANCE: 1.8m ⭕<br></div><div>VALUE: ☹<br></div><div>OTHER SHAPES: ☹<br></div><div>CLAN ZONE: East<br></div><div>HIGHLIGHT: The exit<br></div><div>CLEANLINESS: 🙂<br></div><div>TRANSPORT: Glen Waverley train to Holmesglen<br></div><div>PROBLEMS: Exits on to a private golf course<br></div><div>⛔ 🙂<br></div><div>NEARBY: Dweller’s Tomb, Cordyceps, Mini Tenth, Sloth’s Tomb, Great Stairway, Dougo’s &amp; Cro’s<br></div><div>NOTES: A nice easy drain with a couple of features. Flood control gate added to lake outside in 2007.<br></div><div>Bad was named because it was “bayyd”, just like the Michael Jackson song of the same name.<br></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_0920FA33F53E916505AE</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>145.100553,-37.865142,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="5984C714B8000032">
			<name>Nongdedan</name>
			<snippet></snippet>
			<description><![CDATA[<div>Nongdedan<br></div><div>🚲 🚫 🍸<br></div><div>GPS -37.992324, 145.216196<br></div><div>MELWAYS REF. 90 E-9<br></div><div>LOCATION: East of Lonsdale St (Princes Hwy) on Dandenong Ck<br></div><div>ENTRANCE: 2.4m ⭕<br></div><div>CLAN ZONE: South<br></div><div>⛔ 🙂<br></div><div>TRANSPORT: Train to Dandenong<br></div><div>CLEANLINESS: May stink<br></div><div>HIGHLIGHT: Split room<br></div><div>VALUE: 🏆<br></div><div>PROBLEMS: Sometimes smells bad<br></div><div>NEARBY: MWOTH<br></div><div>NOTES: Has adjoining tunnels to small parallel tunnel.<br></div><div>Nongdedan was so called because apparently only shit drains are named after their suburbs. This drain is in Dandenong.<br></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
